TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sleep Deprivation and Decision-Making Teams: Burning the Midnight Oil or Playing with Fire?
AU  - Barnes, Christopher M.
AU  - Hollenbeck, John R.
Y1  - 2009/01/01
PY  - 2009
DA  - 2009/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.35713280
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2009.35713280
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 56
EP  - 66
VL  - 34
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We introduce the construct of sleep deprivation to the team-level management literature by integrating theory and research on sleep deprivation and group behavior. We propose that sleep deprivation has a negative monotonic, but nonlinear, influence on team decision-making accuracy and problem solving. We then propose that task, structural, and social characteristics accentuate or attenuate the influence of sleep deprivation on team decision-making accuracy and problem solving.
AB  - We introduce the construct of sleep deprivation to the team-level management literature by integrating theory and research on sleep deprivation and group behavior. We propose that sleep deprivation has a negative monotonic, but nonlinear, influence on team decision-making accuracy and problem solving. We then propose that task, structural, and social characteristics accentuate or attenuate the influence of sleep deprivation on team decision-making accuracy and problem solving.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.35713280
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.2009.35713280
Y2  - 2026/04/24
